    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Why Nader Belongs in the Race</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Miles Lott letter concedes there may be a point in remarks about Ralph Nader's ego pushing his presidential campaign, but notes his pertinent remarks about candidates and corporations (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I appreciate your June 30 editorial ''Mr. Nader's Misguided Crusade,'' acknowledging the political power of Ralph Nader and the Green Party. But before you declare him a spoiler, consider that he has already won a partial election victory.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I appreciate your June 30 editorial ''Mr. Nader's Misguided Crusade,'' acknowledging the political power of Ralph Nader and the Green Party. But before you declare him a spoiler, consider that he has already won a partial election victory.</p>
        <p>This week, when Al Gore proposed an energy plan with a light-green tint, he no doubt pulled a few votes from the Nader camp. If Mr. Gore can keep going and co-opt the Green Party positions on campaign reform, labor issues and world trade, he just might take enough votes from Mr. Nader to win the election. And I wouldn't be surprised if Mr. Nader declared such an outcome a victory, exonerating himself of charges of egotism.  GLENN CHENEY  Hanover, Conn., June 30, 2000</p>
      </block>
